						<li class="Comment Reply FLC" comment_id="747687" content_type="article" content_id="19011">	
	<div class="meta">
		<a href="http://www.cracked.com/members/KaliferDeil/" class="Heading5 user" style="float: left;">
		<div style="float:left;"><img src="http://i.crackedcdn.com/phpimages/members/avatars/4/2/270364_45.jpg?1" alt="" class="avatar" style="float:left;"/></div>	
		<div class="username" style="float: left;display: inline;">KaliferDeil</div>
		</a>
		<div style="float:right;">
		<p class="date" style="float:left;"><time datetime="2011-02-21T18:37:14-08:00">02/21/11 06:37 PM</time>
		</p>
           <ul class="Vote">
                            <li class="Note Total_Votes">0</li>
                <li >
                <span class="msg tooltip"><span class="tick"></span></span>
                <button
                                content-type="article"
                                content-id="19011"
                                data-type="comment"
                                data-id="747687"
				data-voted="false"
                                class="rate rate-up Note thumbsUp">1</button></li>
                <li>
                <span class="msg tooltip"><span class="tick"></span></span>
                <button
                                content-type="article"
                                content-id="19011"
                                data-type="comment"
                                data-id="747687"
                                data-voted="false"
                                class="rate rate-down Note thumbsDown">0</button></li>
            </ul>
		</div>
	</div>
	<p class="text">
									Asteroids outside of our orbit can be seen due to reflected sunlight. If they are we closer to the sun than we are then if they are on our side of the sun the lit up side is away from us. On the side of the sun away from us they are lit up from our viewpoint but can only be viewed during the day (with Earth bound telescopes) and due to the distance would be dimmer. The sunlight scattering in out atmosphere would make viewing impossible (which is what you can only see very bright stars during the day). Space based telescopes can block the sunlight and see those that reflect light from the sun. These are expensive and many telescopes are needed to get all those that compose a threat. 						</p>

		
	
		
</li>
